                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d346">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00111A.R.–N.C./21: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-01-30T15:00:00-05:00"
                            >January 30, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 7:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>6. Department’s circular telegram of January 27, 3 p.m. Ecuador regards the
                    Neutrality Committee now in session at Rio as competent to recommend measures
                    arising from problems connected with the Declaration of Panama, being submitted
                    by the Pan American Union to the governments of the American Republics through
                    their representatives at Washington and has so advised its representative at
                    Rio.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
